1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,000
Functions use return to output a single result,

2

00:00:04,000  -->  00:00:07,120
execute all at once when called.

3

00:00:07,120  -->  00:00:09,600
Store all data and memory at once,

4

00:00:09,600  -->  00:00:13,360
can be memory intensive with large datasets.

5

00:00:13,360  -->  00:00:17,500
Typically use for one time calculations for single actions

6

00:00:17,500  -->  00:00:22,360
and do not retain state between calls as each call is independent.

7

00:00:22,360  -->  00:00:24,380
Generators, on the other hand,

8

00:00:24,380  -->  00:00:28,300
use yield to produce a sequence of results one at a time.

9

00:00:28,300  -->  00:00:31,340
Execute in a pause state, resuming,

10

00:00:31,340  -->  00:00:34,480
where it left off are memory efficient,

11

00:00:34,480  -->  00:00:37,320
especially for handling large datasets,

12

00:00:37,320  -->  00:00:44,480
are ideal for processing data in chunks or streams and retain state between yields,

13

00:00:44,480  -->  00:00:47,940
picking up where it left off with each next call.

14

00:00:47,940  -->  00:00:53,550
The things they both have in common are they both are defined using the dev keyword.

15

00:00:53,550  -->  00:00:56,560
They're reusable for repeated tasks.

16

00:00:56,560  -->  00:00:58,740
They can take parameters.

17

00:00:58,740  -->  00:01:04,020
They can be looped over specifically generators with next and functions with loops

18

00:01:04,020  -->  00:01:09,900
inside and are used to break down complex tasks into manageable steps.

19

00:01:09,900  -->  00:01:12,600
If this still feels a bit complicated,

20

00:01:12,600  -->  00:01:14,335
do not worry at all.

21

00:01:14,335  -->  00:01:16,580
We'll dive into some demo examples,

22

00:01:16,580  -->  00:01:20,200
so you can see exactly what we're working with here.
